(446, 1, '2023-05-04 05:13:14', '2023-05-04 05:13:14', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Solutions</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>$(\'a&#91;data-toggle=\"tab\"]\').on(\'shown.bs.tab\', function() {   \n  $($(this).attr(\'href\')).find(\'.slider\').slick({\n    dots: true,\n    arrows: true\n  })\n}).first().trigger(\'shown.bs.tab\');</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Demo</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://jsfiddle.net/vv4j3uz2/7/\">http://jsfiddle.net/vv4j3uz2/7/</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sources </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/48400304/slick-slider-zero-width-in-hidden-container-bootstrap-tab\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/48400304/slick-slider-zero-width-in-hidden-container-bootstrap-tab</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Slick Slider zero width in hidden container (Bootstrap tab)', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '274-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-05-04 05:13:14', '2023-05-04 05:13:14', '', 274, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=446', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(447, 1, '2023-05-04 05:13:41', '2023-05-04 05:13:41', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Selection Sharer is a mobile-friendly social share plugin that shows a floating popover that allows highlighted/selected text to be shared on Facebook, LinkedIn or via email.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On mobile devices, instead of better user experiences, the plugin will screen a social sharing popunder.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It also has the ability, when a Facebook App ID is given, to display the Facebook sharing link inside the share popover.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This Plugin has been used on Nepal Magazine, Medium, and The Kathmandu Post</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>How to use ?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>To use this plugin, you need to make sure \"selection-sharer.css\", \"jQuery\" &amp; \"selection-sharer.js\" files are included correctly.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">&lt;script src=\"//code.jquery.com/jquery.min.js\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"selection-sharer.css\"&gt;\n&lt;script src=\"selection-sharer.js\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 2. Specify the Facebook App ID in the meta tags (OPTIONAL). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">&lt;meta property=\"fb:app_id\" content=\"CONTENT HERE\"&gt;\n&lt;meta property=\"fb:admins\" content=\"CONTENT HERE\"&gt;</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Then initialize the plugin on the target text content and done.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">$(\'p\').selectionSharer();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4.  Or ... </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">var sharer = new SelectionSharer(\'p\');</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. Override the default CSS rules to create your own styles.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">#selectionSharerPopover:after {\n  content: \'\';\n  display: block;\n  position: absolute;\n  bottom: -3px;\n  left: 50%;\n  margin-left: -4px;\n  width: 8px;\n  height: 8px;\n  -webkit-transform: rotate(45deg);\n  transform: rotate(45deg);\n  background: #262625;\n  box-shadow: 0 0 2px #262625;\n}\n\n#selectionSharerPopunder {\n  position: absolute;\n  left: 0;\n  width: 100%;\n  height: 0px;\n  transition: height 0.5s ease-in-out;\n  background: #ccc;\n  border: none;\n  box-shadow: inset 0px 10px 5px -10px rgba(0,0,0,0.5), inset 0px -10px 5px -10px rgba(0,0,0,0.5);\n  border-radius: 0;\n  overflow: hidden;\n}\n</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.jqueryscript.net/demo/Share-Selected-Text-On-Twitter-Email-jQuery-Selection-Sharer/\">DEMO</a>           <a href=\"https://www.jqueryscript.net/download/Share-Selected-Text-On-Twitter-Email-jQuery-Selection-Sharer.zip\">DOWNLOAD</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Selected TEXT share in Social ( Facebook, Twitter, Email)', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '257-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-05-04 05:13:41', '2023-05-04 05:13:41', '', 257, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=447', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(448, 1, '2023-05-04 05:14:41', '2023-05-04 05:14:41', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> This is a Magento bug. Wrong paths to Windows are generated. The fixed fix is </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Magento 2.3.0 - 2.3.3</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Go to </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>vendor/magento/framework/View/Element/Template/File/Validator.php:140</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>the string</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>if (0 === strpos($realPath, $directory)) {\n    return true;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>to replace</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>$realDirectory = $this-&gt;fileDriver-&gt;getRealPath($directory);\nif ($realDirectory &amp;&amp; 0 === strpos($realPath, $realDirectory)) {\n   return true;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Magento 2.2.7</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>/vendor/magento/framework/View/Element/Template/File/Validator.php:113</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>code</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>protected function isPathInDirectories($path, $directories)\n{\n    if (!is_array($directories)) {\n        $directories = (array)$directories;\n    }\n    foreach ($directories as $directory) {\n        if (0 === strpos($this-&gt;fileDriver-&gt;getRealPath($path), $directory)) {\n            return true;\n        }\n    }\n    return false;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>to replace</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>protected function isPathInDirectories($path, $directories)\n    {\n        $realPath = str_replace(\'\\\\\', \'/\', $this-&gt;fileDriver-&gt;getRealPath($path));\n        if (!is_array($directories)) {\n            $directories = (array)$directories;\n        }\n        foreach ($directories as $directory) {\n            if (0 === strpos($realPath, $directory)) {\n                return true;\n            }\n        }\n        return false;\n    }</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If You can\'t find out the (/vendor/magento/framework/) folder in magento 2.2.7 - 2.3.3 . Then You can check it here:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>#lib\\internal\\Magento\\Framework\\View\\Element\\Template\\File\\Validator.php</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->', 'Magento Admin panel blank page', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '263-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-05-04 05:14:41', '2023-05-04 05:14:41', '', 263, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=448', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(449, 1, '2023-05-04 05:15:45', '2023-05-04 05:15:45', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Its very simple and easy to find generations of your laptop or Computer if you you are using laptop or computer then you have running Windows OS it doesn\'t matter. there is lots of quickest finding generations some of them are in below</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are Logged In on Pc/Laptop</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Go to My Pc </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Right Click on My Properties and you will see this text [ i have red marked and pointed on 4 digit number]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":212} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://ayushshrestha.com.np/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/image-1024x605.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-212\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3.  Now you will 4 Digit number and the first you see is Generations ex. if you see 5500 it will be first digit is 5 so it will be 5th Generation if you see 3210 so it will be 3 Generations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Find Windows OS Computer or Laptop\'s Generations', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '209-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-05-04 05:15:45', '2023-05-04 05:15:45', '', 209, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=449', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(455, 1, '2023-05-04 05:17:41', '2023-05-04 05:17:41', 'Think about how you load different types of resources on the web. For JS, we have&nbsp;<code>&lt;script src&gt;</code>. For CSS, your go-to is probably&nbsp;<code>&lt;link rel=\"stylesheet\"&gt;</code>. For images it\'s&nbsp;<code>&lt;img&gt;</code>. Video has&nbsp;<code>&lt;video&gt;</code>. Audio,&nbsp;<code>&lt;audio&gt;</code>.... Get to the point! The majority of the web\'s content has a simple and declarative way to load itself. Not so for HTML. Here\'s your options:\n<ol>\n 	<li><strong><code>&lt;iframe&gt;</code></strong>&nbsp;- tried and true but heavy weight. An iframe\'s content lives entirely in a separate context than your page. While that\'s mostly a great feature, it creates additional challenges (shrink wrapping the size of the frame to its content is tough, insanely frustrating to script into/out of, nearly impossible to style).</li>\n 	<li><strong>AJAX</strong>&nbsp;-&nbsp;<a href=\"http://ericbidelman.tumblr.com/post/31140607367/mashups-using-cors-and-responsetype-document\">I love&nbsp;<code>xhr.responseType=\"document\"</code></a>, but you\'re saying I need JS to load HTML? That doesn\'t seem right.</li>\n 	<li><strong>CrazyHacks™</strong>&nbsp;- embedded in strings, hidden as comments (e.g.&nbsp;<code>&lt;script type=\"text/html\"&gt;</code>). Yuck!</li>\n</ol>\nSee the irony?&nbsp;<strong>The web\'s most basic content, HTML, requires the greatest amount of effort to work with</strong>. Fortunately,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://w3c.github.io/webcomponents/explainer/\">Web Components</a>&nbsp;are here to get us back on track.\n<h2 id=\"started\">Getting started\n\n<a href=\"https://www.html5rocks.com/en/tutorials/webcomponents/imports/\">Read More ?</a></h2>\n&nbsp;', 'Why Import?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '33-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-05-04 05:17:41', '2023-05-04 05:17:41', '', 33, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=455', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(457, 1, '2023-05-04 05:17:57', '2023-05-04 05:17:57', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>HTML<br></strong><br>Scroll Down        Keep Going! You Made It!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>CSS</strong><br><br>body{<br>     border:0;<br>     font-family:arial;<br>     font-size:50px;<br>     line-height:500px;  <br>     margin:0 auto;<br>     padding:0;<br>     text-align:center;<br>     width:960px;<br>   }<br>   #header{<br>     background:#faa;<br>     height:500px;<br>   }<br>   #footer{<br>     background:#aaf;<br>     height:500px;<br>   }<br>   #main{<br>     background:#afa;<br>     height: 1800px;<br>     line-height:1800px;<br>     position: relative;<br>   }<br>     #container{<br>        background: none repeat scroll 0 0 orange;<br>        height: 200px;<br>        position: absolute;<br>        right: 10px;<br>        top: 10px;<br>        width: 200px;<br>     }</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>JQUERY</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>jQuery(document).ready(function($){<br>\n    //variables<br>\n    var $window = $(window);<br>\n    var $container = $(\"#container\");<br>\n    var $main = $(\"#main\");<br>\n    var window_min = 0;<br>\n    var window_max = 0;<br>\n    var threshold_offset = 50;<br>\n    /*<br>\n     set the container\'s maximum and minimum limits as well as movement thresholds<br>\n    <em>/\n    function set_limits(){\n        //max and min container movements\n        var max_move = $main.offset().top + $main.height() - $container.height() - 2</em>parseInt($container.css(\"top\") );<br>\n        var min_move = $main.offset().top;<br>\n        //save them<br>\n        $container.attr(\"data-min\", min_move).attr(\"data-max\",max_move);<br>\n        //window thresholds so the movement isn\'t called when its not needed!<br>\n        //you may wish to adjust the freshhold offset<br>\n        window_min = min_move - threshold_offset;<br>\n        window_max = max_move + $container.height() + threshold_offset;<br>\n    }<br>\n    //sets the limits for the first load<br>\n    set_limits();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>function window_scroll(){\n    //if the window is within the threshold, begin movements\n    if( $window.scrollTop() &gt;= window_min &amp;&amp; $window.scrollTop() &lt; window_max ){\n        //reset the limits (optional)\n        set_limits();\n        //move the container\n        container_move();\n    }\n}\n$window.bind(\"scroll\", window_scroll);\n\n/**\n * Handles moving the container if needed.\n**/\nfunction container_move(){\n    var wst = $window.scrollTop();\n    //if the window scroll is within the min and max (the container will be \"sticky\";\n    if( wst &gt;= $container.attr(\"data-min\") &amp;&amp; wst &lt;= $container.attr(\"data-max\") ){\n        //work out the margin offset\n        var margin_top = $window.scrollTop() - $container.attr(\"data-min\");\n        //margin it down!\n        $container.css(\"margin-top\", margin_top);\n    //if the window scroll is below the minimum \n    }else if( wst &lt;= $container.attr(\"data-min\") ){\n        //fix the container to the top.\n        $container.css(\"margin-top\",0);\n    //if the window scroll is above the maximum \n    }else if( wst &gt; $container.attr(\"data-max\") ){\n        //fix the container to the top\n        $container.css(\"margin-top\", $container.attr(\"data-max\")-$container.attr(\"data-min\")+\"px\" );\n    }\n}\n//do one container move on load\ncontainer_move();</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>});</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {\"url\":\"https://codepen.io/hitreach/pen/bLmrC\",\"type\":\"rich\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"codepen\",\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-codepen\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://codepen.io/hitreach/pen/bLmrC\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->', 'Scrolling Container With Bounds', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '206-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-05-04 05:17:57', '2023-05-04 05:17:57', '', 206, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=457', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(463, 1, '2023-06-21 16:59:20', '2023-06-21 16:59:20', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Add this code in Tailwind.config.js<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>purge: [ </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\'**/*.php\',</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\'*.php\',</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>],</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '[SOLVED] - Tailwind.config.js purge option doesn\'t recognise PHP files and causes infinite recompiling', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'solved-tailwind-config-js-purge-option-doesnt-recognise-php-files-and-causes-infinite-recompiling', '', '', '2023-06-21 17:01:36', '2023-06-21 17:01:36', '', 0, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=463', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(464, 1, '2023-06-21 16:59:20', '2023-06-21 16:59:20', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Add this code in Tailwind.config.js<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>purge: [ </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\'**/*.php\',</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\'*.php\',</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>],</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '[SOLVED] - Tailwind.config.js purge option doesn\'t recognise PHP files and causes infinite recompiling', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '463-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-06-21 16:59:20', '2023-06-21 16:59:20', '', 463, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=464', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(465, 1, '2023-06-21 17:01:19', '2023-06-21 17:01:19', 'Wordpress TailwindCSS', 'Wordpress TailwindCSS', 'Wordpress TailwindCSS', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', 'wordpress-tailwindcss', '', '', '2023-06-21 17:01:33', '2023-06-21 17:01:33', '', 463, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/wordpress-tailwindcss.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(466, 1, '2023-06-28 06:08:12', '2023-06-28 06:08:12', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Question 1:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I am using AOS to show html elements on scroll. It works well alone, but when I use it on the pages that contains Slick slider, the elements on which is AOS applied are not showing. Elements are hidden and if there is a lot scroll, it looks like the browser gives wrong information to AOS about current scrolling position and some elements are shown latter.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is no specific code that makes this problems, any usage of slick on the same page with AOS makes AOS not working.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Did anyone solved this problem, I saw some pending questions on other websites and didn\'t find any solution?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Answers 1: </strong><br>In my case, I put AOS refresh after slick initializations</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>$(window).on(\'load\', function() {\n\n  <strong>  AOS.init({\n        duration: 600,\n        once: true\n    });</strong>\n\n    $(\'.slick-hero\').slick({\n        dots: true,\n        infinite: true,\n        slidesToShow: 2,\n        slidesToScroll: 2\n    });\n\n    $(\'.slick-hero\').slick({\n        dots: true,\n        infinite: true,\n        slidesToShow: 2,\n        slidesToScroll: 2\n    });\n\n    $(\'.slick-hero\').slick({\n        dots: true,\n        infinite: true,\n        slidesToShow: 5,\n        slidesToScroll: 5\n    });\n\n    <strong>AOS.refresh();</strong>\n});</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->', '[Solved] - How to make AOS not working with Slick slider?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'solved-how-to-make-aos-not-working-with-slick-slider', '', '', '2023-06-28 06:11:38', '2023-06-28 06:11:38', '', 0, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=466', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(467, 1, '2023-06-28 06:05:35', '2023-06-28 06:05:35', 'Slick Slider with AOS', 'Slick Slider with AOS', 'Slick Slider with AOS', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', 'slick-slider-with-aos', '', '', '2023-06-28 06:05:48', '2023-06-28 06:05:48', '', 466, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/slick-slider-with-aos.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(468, 1, '2023-06-28 06:08:12', '2023-06-28 06:08:12', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Question 1:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I am using AOS to show html elements on scroll. It works well alone, but when I use it on the pages that contains Slick slider, the elements on which is AOS applied are not showing. Elements are hidden and if there is a lot scroll, it looks like the browser gives wrong information to AOS about current scrolling position and some elements are shown latter.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is no specific code that makes this problems, any usage of slick on the same page with AOS makes AOS not working.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Did anyone solved this problem, I saw some pending questions on other websites and didn\'t find any solution?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Answers 1: </strong><br>In my case, I put AOS refresh after slick initializations</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n$(window).on(\'load\', function() {\n\n    AOS.init({\n        duration: 600,\n        once: true\n    });\n\n    $(\'.section-product-container\').slick({\n        dots: true,\n        infinite: true,\n        slidesToShow: 3,\n        slidesToScroll: 3,\n    });\n\n    $(\'.slide-container\').slick({\n        dots: true,\n        infinite: true,\n        slidesToShow: 1,\n        slidesToScroll: 1,\n        arrows: true,\n        speed: 300,\n        autoplay: true,\n        fade: true,\n        cssEase: \'linear\',\n        customPaging : function(slider, i) {\n            var number = (i+1);\n            if ((i+1) < 10)\n                number = \'0\'+(i+1);\n            return \'<a>\'+ number +\'</a>\';\n        }\n    });\n\n    $(\'.section-customer-container\').slick({\n        dots: true,\n        infinite: true,\n        slidesToShow: 5,\n        slidesToScroll: 5,\n        customPaging : function(slider, i) {\n            if ((i+1) < 10)\n                return \'<a>0\'+(i+1)+\'</a>\';\n            return \'<a>\'+ i +\'</a>\';\n        }\n    });\n\n    AOS.refresh();\n});\n<!-- /wp:html -->', '[Solved] - How to make AOS not working with Slick slider?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '466-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-06-28 06:08:12', '2023-06-28 06:08:12', '', 466, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=468', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(473, 1, '2023-07-07 12:43:13', '2023-07-07 12:43:13', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another day, another brand-new app claiming to be Twitter\'s replacement.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As soon as Elon Musk acquired control of Twitter last year, the hierarchy of text-based social media platforms began to appear unstable. As he continues to implement jarring and unpopular changes on the platform, the instability has only increased.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This has led to a plethora of rivals fighting for Twitter\'s cherished crown, the most recent of which is Threads, which was revealed late Wednesday by Meta, the parent company of Facebook.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With 30 million users in less than 24 hours, Threads already seems to have an advantage over other Twitter rivals.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But might it go all the way and put Twitter out of business? It might not be that easy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>First things first: What connects Twitter and Threads?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Threads is being marketed by Meta as a brand-new platform for real-time, open dialogue. Additionally, despite being closely related to Instagram (users must have an Instagram account to sign up), the user experience is very similar to Twitter.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Musk is allegedly \"breaking things\" and moving quickly, according to the former head of safety at Twitter.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The software chooses simplicity above glitzy new features in terms of utility.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, rather than in spite of it, it\'s possible that people are flocking to Threads as a result of that fact.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Okay, but what sets this apart from Twitter clones Mastodon, Hive Social, Blue Sky, etc.?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Data and scale are the two factors that provide Threads an advantage over its rivals.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Existing Instagram users who download the new app have the ability to import basic setup elements like their bio, username, profile photo, and follow list.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You want to stop using Twitter. The social networks listed here currently have new users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Celebrities like Zac Efron, Shakira, and chef Gordan Ramsay are among the users. Threads was being used by news organizations like CBS, Vox, and Vogue as well as companies like Airbnb, Netflix, Marvel Studios, and Spotify.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Over a million tweets about \"Threads\" were sent out as a result of the excitement on its rival platform. Tech enthusiasts are calling the newcomer the \"Twitter killer.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>How many customers does that have compared to Twitter?</strong><br>Twitter doesn\'t regularly provide information about its user base, especially since it was discovered in 2017 that it had been inflating the number of monthly active users for years. Around that time, the company counted 326 million active monthly users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One thing to keep in mind is that Mark Zuckerberg, the owner of Meta, could have easily launched Threads at that time or even earlier. In 2008, he attempted to acquire Twitter on his own, but the company refused to sell.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Musk only put a temporary cap on the number of tweets non-paying users might access each day over the weekend. Twitter also rapidly changed its decision to make it impossible to access tweets without being logged into the service.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Even after months of unrest, each new policy change prompts a flood of tweets from users who are considering abandoning the network. At the same time, Twitter\'s advertising spending has plummeted, falling by almost 60% from a year ago.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NPR has reached out to Musk for comment on the debut of Threads, although he has previously called its sibling app, Instagram, \"weak sauce.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In a tweet posted on Thursday, he said, \"It is infinitely preferable to be attacked by strangers on Twitter, than indulge in the false happiness of hide-the-pain Instagram.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Is Threads really a \'Twitter killer\'?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'is-threads-really-a-twitter-killer', '', '', '2023-07-07 12:46:54', '2023-07-07 12:46:54', '', 0, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=473', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(459, 1, '2023-05-04 05:18:12', '2023-05-04 05:18:12', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The 500 internal server error runs on every page of your site when there’s a problem with the server or file system that’s powering your site. The cause most likely occurs in the root directory, where your WordPress files are, but it can also be caused by a problem on your host’s server.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is one of the most frustrating errors that can occur in WordPress. It never has a straightforward solution, requiring a lot of troubleshooting that can eat up your time and patience. But we’re going to try to help alleviate some of that stress by suggesting several solutions to this problem and walking you through each.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s get started.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {\"url\":\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-Ugh_ynhIfI\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"youtube\",\"responsive\":true,\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-Ugh_ynhIfI\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->', 'Fix 500 Internal Server Error Wordpress', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '153-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-05-04 05:18:12', '2023-05-04 05:18:12', '', 153, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=459', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(460, 1, '2023-05-04 05:18:18', '2023-05-04 05:18:18', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You\'ve probably seen this pattern going around. It\'s an input that appears as if it has placeholder text in it, but when you click/tap into that input, that text moves out of the way and allows you to type there. It\'s rather clever, I think. Brad Frost has&nbsp;<a href=\"http://bradfrostweb.com/blog/post/float-label-pattern/\">a really good post on it</a>, detailing the pros and cons and such.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Many of the demos I\'ve seen involve JavaScript. The other day I was checking out at Nest.com, saw their technique for it, and I thought of a way I could pull that off without JavaScript. So here we are.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here\'s how the Nest.com one looks:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {\"url\":\"https://codepen.io/chriscoyier/pen/CiflJ\",\"type\":\"rich\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"codepen\",\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-codepen\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://codepen.io/chriscoyier/pen/CiflJ\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It\'s not quite as sexy as the Nest ones, where the text is fading out as the label is sliding up. Certainly possible with some JavaScript, but we\'re going to stick with pure CSS here. Still might be possible though. I\'ll leave that challenge up to you.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"article-header-id-0\"><a href=\"https://css-tricks.com/float-labels-css/#article-header-id-0\">#</a>Some Quick Reminders</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are two reasons you might consider doing this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>It might be able to save space.</strong>&nbsp;Because the input and label are combined, it takes up less space. When an input is in focus, you do still need to show both the label and input, but you can get that space by either using some of the space the input was already using, or by growing the area temporarily only for the focused input.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>It makes the input one big button.</strong>&nbsp;Not that inputs aren\'t already, and not that labels aren\'t when they have a proper&nbsp;<code>for</code>&nbsp;attribute, but there is something kinda nice about a big rectangle that tells you what it wants that you click/tap. Might make for a nice experience particularly on mobile.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'d say, generally, that always-visible labels are probably \"better\" - but this is a clever idea and done right, may be useful occasionally. There is always a risk of screwing this up and hurting accessibility too, so take care. One downside to this pattern: we can\'t use&nbsp;<code>placeholder</code>&nbsp;in addition to the label, which can be helpful (e.g. a label of \"Phone Number\" and a placeholder hint of \"(555) 555-5555\").</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"article-header-id-1\"><a href=\"https://css-tricks.com/float-labels-css/#article-header-id-1\">#</a>The Trick (1 of 3) - The label is the placeholder</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is a&nbsp;<code>&lt;div&gt;</code>&nbsp;that contains both the&nbsp;<code>&lt;label&gt;</code>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<code>&lt;input&gt;</code>&nbsp;(which you need to do anyway because inputs within forms need to be in block level elements) that has relative positioning. That allows absolute positioning within it, which means we can position the label and input on top of each other. If we do that with the input on top, but with a transparent background, you\'ll be able to see the label right underneath it while still being able click into it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://css-tricks.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/label-in-middle.svg\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;div&gt;\n  &lt;input id=\"name\" name=\"name\" type=\"text\" required&gt;\n  &lt;label for=\"name\"&gt;Your Name&lt;/label&gt;\n&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>form &gt; div {\n  position: relative;\n}\nform &gt; div &gt; label {\n  position: absolute;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"article-header-id-2\"><a href=\"https://css-tricks.com/float-labels-css/#article-header-id-2\">#</a>The Trick (2 of 3) - the :focus state and the adjacent sibling combinator</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The source order of the&nbsp;<code>&lt;label&gt;</code>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<code>&lt;input&gt;</code>&nbsp;wouldn\'t matter much here, since semantically they are tied together with the&nbsp;<code>for</code>&nbsp;attribute. But if we put the input first, that means we can leverage its&nbsp;<code>:focus</code>&nbsp;state and an adjacent sibling combinator (+) to affect the label when it is focused. Similar in concept to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://css-tricks.com/the-checkbox-hack/\">checkbox hack</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>input:focus + label {\n  /* do something with the label */\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can do whatever you want with the label. Just find a cool place to move it and style it that is out of the way of typing in the input. My example had two possibilities: one was making it smaller and moving toward the bottom of the input, the other was moving it to the far right side.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>form.go-bottom label {\n  position: absolute;\n  top: 0;\n  bottom: 0;\n  left: 0;\n  width: 100%;\n  transition: 0.2s;\n}\nform.go-bottom input:focus + label\n  top: 100%;\n  margin-top: -16px;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"article-header-id-3\"><a href=\"https://css-tricks.com/float-labels-css/#article-header-id-3\">#</a>The Trick (3 of 3) - the :valid state</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once there is actual text in the input, and the input goes back&nbsp;<em>out</em>&nbsp;of focus, it would be very weird (bad) to see the label and the input text on top of each other. Fortunately in CSS there is a&nbsp;<code>:valid</code>selector that works on inputs when they are in a valid state. That valid state can be \"any text at all\", assuming the only thing that makes it valid is having any value at all, which can be achieved like:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;input type=\"text\" required&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then remember the only reason you could see the label at all was because the input has a transparent background. To hide it, we can use an opaque background instead:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>form input:valid {\n  background: white;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The rest of this is just fiddling around with design details until you have it just how you like it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Float Labels with CSS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '197-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-05-04 05:18:18', '2023-05-04 05:18:18', '', 197, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=460', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(471, 1, '2023-06-28 06:11:38', '2023-06-28 06:11:38', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Question 1:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I am using AOS to show html elements on scroll. It works well alone, but when I use it on the pages that contains Slick slider, the elements on which is AOS applied are not showing. Elements are hidden and if there is a lot scroll, it looks like the browser gives wrong information to AOS about current scrolling position and some elements are shown latter.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is no specific code that makes this problems, any usage of slick on the same page with AOS makes AOS not working.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Did anyone solved this problem, I saw some pending questions on other websites and didn\'t find any solution?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Answers 1: </strong><br>In my case, I put AOS refresh after slick initializations</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>$(window).on(\'load\', function() {\n\n  <strong>  AOS.init({\n        duration: 600,\n        once: true\n    });</strong>\n\n    $(\'.slick-hero\').slick({\n        dots: true,\n        infinite: true,\n        slidesToShow: 2,\n        slidesToScroll: 2\n    });\n\n    $(\'.slick-hero\').slick({\n        dots: true,\n        infinite: true,\n        slidesToShow: 2,\n        slidesToScroll: 2\n    });\n\n    $(\'.slick-hero\').slick({\n        dots: true,\n        infinite: true,\n        slidesToShow: 5,\n        slidesToScroll: 5\n    });\n\n    <strong>AOS.refresh();</strong>\n});</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->', '[Solved] - How to make AOS not working with Slick slider?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '466-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-06-28 06:11:38', '2023-06-28 06:11:38', '', 466, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=471', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(470, 1, '2023-06-28 06:09:35', '2023-06-28 06:09:35', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Question 1:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I am using AOS to show html elements on scroll. It works well alone, but when I use it on the pages that contains Slick slider, the elements on which is AOS applied are not showing. Elements are hidden and if there is a lot scroll, it looks like the browser gives wrong information to AOS about current scrolling position and some elements are shown latter.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is no specific code that makes this problems, any usage of slick on the same page with AOS makes AOS not working.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Did anyone solved this problem, I saw some pending questions on other websites and didn\'t find any solution?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Answers 1: </strong><br>In my case, I put AOS refresh after slick initializations</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>$(window).on(\'load\', function() {\n\n  <strong>  AOS.init({\n        duration: 600,\n        once: true\n    });</strong>\n\n    $(\'.section-product-container\').slick({\n        dots: true,\n        infinite: true,\n        slidesToShow: 3,\n        slidesToScroll: 3,\n    });\n\n    $(\'.slide-container\').slick({\n        dots: true,\n        infinite: true,\n        slidesToShow: 1,\n        slidesToScroll: 1,\n        arrows: true,\n        speed: 300,\n        autoplay: true,\n        fade: true,\n        cssEase: \'linear\',\n        customPaging : function(slider, i) {\n            var number = (i+1);\n            if ((i+1) &lt; 10)\n                number = \'0\'+(i+1);\n            return \'&lt;a>\'+ number +\'&lt;/a>\';\n        }\n    });\n\n    $(\'.section-customer-container\').slick({\n        dots: true,\n        infinite: true,\n        slidesToShow: 5,\n        slidesToScroll: 5,\n        customPaging : function(slider, i) {\n            if ((i+1) &lt; 10)\n                return \'&lt;a>0\'+(i+1)+\'&lt;/a>\';\n            return \'&lt;a>\'+ i +\'&lt;/a>\';\n        }\n    });\n\n    <strong>AOS.refresh();</strong>\n});</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->', '[Solved] - How to make AOS not working with Slick slider?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '466-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-06-28 06:09:35', '2023-06-28 06:09:35', '', 466, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=470', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(474, 1, '2023-07-07 12:43:13', '2023-07-07 12:43:13', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another day, another brand-new app claiming to be Twitter\'s replacement.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As soon as Elon Musk acquired control of Twitter last year, the hierarchy of text-based social media platforms began to appear unstable. As he continues to implement jarring and unpopular changes on the platform, the instability has only increased.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This has led to a plethora of rivals fighting for Twitter\'s cherished crown, the most recent of which is Threads, which was revealed late Wednesday by Meta, the parent company of Facebook.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With 30 million users in less than 24 hours, Threads already seems to have an advantage over other Twitter rivals.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But might it go all the way and put Twitter out of business? It might not be that easy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>First things first: What connects Twitter and Threads?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Threads is being marketed by Meta as a brand-new platform for real-time, open dialogue. Additionally, despite being closely related to Instagram (users must have an Instagram account to sign up), the user experience is very similar to Twitter.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Musk is allegedly \"breaking things\" and moving quickly, according to the former head of safety at Twitter.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The software chooses simplicity above glitzy new features in terms of utility.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, rather than in spite of it, it\'s possible that people are flocking to Threads as a result of that fact.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Okay, but what sets this apart from Twitter clones Mastodon, Hive Social, Blue Sky, etc.?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Data and scale are the two factors that provide Threads an advantage over its rivals.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Existing Instagram users who download the new app have the ability to import basic setup elements like their bio, username, profile photo, and follow list.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You want to stop using Twitter. The social networks listed here currently have new users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Celebrities like Zac Efron, Shakira, and chef Gordan Ramsay are among the users. Threads was being used by news organizations like CBS, Vox, and Vogue as well as companies like Airbnb, Netflix, Marvel Studios, and Spotify.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Over a million tweets about \"Threads\" were sent out as a result of the excitement on its rival platform. Tech enthusiasts are calling the newcomer the \"Twitter killer.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>How many customers does that have compared to Twitter?</strong><br>Twitter doesn\'t regularly provide information about its user base, especially since it was discovered in 2017 that it had been inflating the number of monthly active users for years. Around that time, the company counted 326 million active monthly users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One thing to keep in mind is that Mark Zuckerberg, the owner of Meta, could have easily launched Threads at that time or even earlier. In 2008, he attempted to acquire Twitter on his own, but the company refused to sell.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Musk only put a temporary cap on the number of tweets non-paying users might access each day over the weekend. Twitter also rapidly changed its decision to make it impossible to access tweets without being logged into the service.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Even after months of unrest, each new policy change prompts a flood of tweets from users who are considering abandoning the network. At the same time, Twitter\'s advertising spending has plummeted, falling by almost 60% from a year ago.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NPR has reached out to Musk for comment on the debut of Threads, although he has previously called its sibling app, Instagram, \"weak sauce.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In a tweet posted on Thursday, he said, \"It is infinitely preferable to be attacked by strangers on Twitter, than indulge in the false happiness of hide-the-pain Instagram.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Is Threads really a \'Twitter killer\'?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '473-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-07-07 12:43:13', '2023-07-07 12:43:13', '', 473, 'https://www.ayushshrestha.com.np/?p=474', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
